<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>To: E		Environmental Audit Committee</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written Evidence </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Submitted </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">by Centriforce Products Ltd</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Centriforce Products does not oppose any levy on ‘single use’ plastic bags </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Centriforce Products, as an established reprocesssor of waste plastic materials [see introduction below], has major concerns about the incorporation of ‘biodegradable materials’ or ‘oxo-degradabale’ plastics within the UK recycled plastic supply chain as a result of the specific requirement for these material to degrade and hence impact the property profile and lifetime expectations of the material in ‘second-use’ applications </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We question DEFRA’s desire to allow a levy exemption for degradable materials into the UK marketplace based on DEFRA’s own published research  on the efficacy of the environmental performance of degradable materials </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">With extensive experience of the output of UK  Material Recycling Facilities (‘MRF’), we do not believe that it will be possible to efficiently sort degradable materials from general waste plastic materials and as  result could potentially severely damage a well established recycling and reprocessing marketplace due to lack of confidence from end-use customers on the integrity of recycled plastic products</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As stated by the British Retail Consortium in its submission to DEFRA at a recent Industry workshop, we strongly believe that the introduction of degradable plastic bags will both confuse the consumer and potentially actually lead to increased litter as  result of the consumer believing that these materials will simply degrade when disposed of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction to Centriforce Products Ltd </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Centriforce Products Ltd is a UK based recycler and reprocessor of waste plastic materials based in Liverpool, UK.  The company has nearly 35 year experience of working with waste plastics materials  and helped pioneer ma</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">y of the current methodologies used to process waste plastic materials as well as having worked closely with DEFRA’s agency</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">WRAP</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on application development of ‘second use’ materials over many years.  It is now one of the countries leading independent plastic recyclers serving the UK market with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">second use</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> products for a diverse range of applications within the UK as well as exporting these same products overseas.  Centriforce Products sources its feedstock both from the marketplace and also direct from some major household brands including UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">retailers. </span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Supporting evidence</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">i)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">DEFRA’s Report on ‘Oxo-degradables’, 2010</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> concluded that “….the incorporation of additives into petroleum based plastics …..does not improve their environmental impact and potentially gives rise to certain negative effects” </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ii)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The Environment Agency  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Life Cycle Assessment of supermarket carrier bags 2011</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> recognised that the ‘single use’ carrier bag  performs well in relation to alternative materials when considered from a full life cycle perspective. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">iii)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">A report commissioned by European Plastics Converters (EuPC), 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> indicated that ‘quantities as low as 2% degradable plastic films cause significant detrimental impact on the quality of plastics recyclates  owing to reduced mechanical properties and significant visual impact on newly produced films</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">iv)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Sortation is not currently possible in the recycled plastic supply chain.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Centriforce Products knows from its own experience that contamination levels of 10% + are common in the output levels of UK MRF’s at the current time </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> We are firmly of the belief based on many years of experience of having worked in the UK recycled plastic marketplace that it will not be possible to remove degradable plastics from the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘recyclate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> chain</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Even a small residual percentage of degradable materials in the feedstock would have far reaching and potentially devastating effects on customers for recycled materials.    </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">v)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Recycled plastic products are often designed to have a long application life </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and in fact their unique selling proposition is often their ability </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be used to replace traditional materials (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">often timber</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">) for applications where the timber would be expected to decay or rot in a short period of time </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">vi)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Littering and environmental persistence.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Incorporation of degradable plastic bags at retailers would only serve to confuse the consumer.  For many years, the consumer has been encouraged to either prevent materials from being wasted or</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> if the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">y</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> must be disposed of then they should be recycled. There is evidence to suggest that in recent years the consumer has started to respond to these messages</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">G</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">overnment has set stretching targets for the coming 5 year period for plastic packaging recycling rates.  Assuming a degradable bag was exempt from a levy, what should the consumer then do with these bags?  The recycling market does not want degradable materials f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">or</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the reasons stated earlier.   The composters do not want degradable plastic in their feedstock as they contaminate organic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> compostable materials and do not break down sufficient</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> quickly. Hence for most consumers, this would mean the material being added to their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">non recyclable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> waste bin and therefore would directly oppose The Government’s targets for recycling of plastic packaging.   </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">9 December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>